## Status: COMPLETED ✅

## Summary

Implemented M3.1 (separate /ready from /health) and M3.4 (structured per-call log)
on top of the M1+M2 instrumentation foundation. The /ready endpoint returns 503
until `build_graph` has succeeded, then 200; the dispatch boundary now emits one
structured `tracing::info!` line per tool call with `tool`, `duration_ms`, and
`status` fields.

## Tasks Completed

### M3.1 — /ready endpoint

- [x] Added `graph_loaded: Arc<AtomicBool>` field to `HandlerContext`
  (`crates/cognicode-core/src/interface/mcp/handlers/mod.rs`).
- [x] Added helper methods `mark_graph_loaded()` and `is_graph_loaded()`.
- [x] Updated 3 struct-literal initializers (2 deprecated constructors + the
  builder's `build()`).
- [x] Updated `Debug` impl to show the flag's current value.
- [x] Added `CogniCodeHandler::from_ctx(ctx: Arc<HandlerContext>)` constructor
  to share a pre-built `HandlerContext` between the MCP dispatch (per session)
  and the HTTP `/ready` handler (`crates/cognicode-core/src/interface/mcp/rmcp_adapter.rs`).
- [x] After successful `build_graph` in `call_tool_handler`, call
  `ctx.mark_graph_loaded()`.
- [x] Modified `crates/cognicode-mcp/src/server.rs` to:
  - Build a single shared `Arc<HandlerContext>` in `main()`.
  - Use `CogniCodeHandler::from_ctx(shared_ctx.clone())` in the
    `StreamableHttpService` factory so each session shares the same context.
  - Add `async fn ready_handler(State(ctx): State<Arc<HandlerContext>>)` that
    returns `(200, {"status":"ready","graph_loaded":true})` when the flag is
    set, otherwise `(503, {"status":"not_ready","graph_loaded":false})`.
  - Register the route via `.route("/ready", get(ready_handler))` and
    `.with_state(shared_ctx)`.

### M3.4 — Structured per-call log

- [x] Added `tracing::info!(tool, duration_ms, status, "tool_call")` at the
  end of `call_tool_handler` boundary, after `classify_status` is computed
  and before OTel metrics recording. Emits exactly one log line per tool
  call regardless of success/error/gated/missing/skipped status.
- [x] `tracing` was already imported in `rmcp_adapter.rs` via existing
  usage, so no new import was needed.

